{What we are about to examine is a flexible system where White keeps his
options open and adapts to Black's choice of pawn formation.} 1. d4 d5 (1...
Nf6 {This move became popular early in the 20th century when Black devised a
number of ways of fighting against White's big center in the d-pawn openings
without (usually) playing a quick ...d5 himself. One obvious point relevant to
our choice of openings is that Black reserves the right to play ...d6, in
which case a Stonewall setup is not reasonable.} 2. Nf3 {This is the most
flexible way for White to proceed. If he commits too quickly to a Stonewall,
Black will just play ...d6 and White's pieces will not be well placed. In
particular, Black might prepare and execute the thrust ...e5 right in the
teeth of White's Stonewall structure -- not something White wants to see
happen!} 2... d5 {With this order of moves, Black suceeds in making White
commit to Nf3 earlier than in the 1.d4 d5 2.e3 lines. Against most other 2nd
moves, White will bring out his darksquare Bishop.} (2... e6 3. Bg5 {is the mai
n line of the Torre Attack, named for the Mexican master who used this system
regularly in the 1920s.}) (2... g6 3. Bg5 {is another line of the Torre Attack,
useful against Black's "King's Indian" pawn structure.}) (2... c5 {
With this move, Black offers to play the Benoni Defense.} 3. c3 $5 {American GM
Gata Kamsky often plays this simple move, keeping his d-pawn on a dark square
and keeping open his options for the development of his minor pieces and the
placement of his e-pawn.} (3. d5 {is the most common response, and it is good
-- but it leads to positions of great complexity that Black has probably
studied deeply.})) {When Black has combined ...Nf6 with ...d5, White should
simply head for a Colle System with} 3. e3 {Now Black has several options:} (3.
Bf4 {is also a very reasonable move, initiating a setup known as the London
System. Usually White follows up with typical "Colle" moves like e3, Bd3 (or
perhaps Be2 if Black has pinned with ...Bg4), Nbd2, c3, and 0-0.}) (3. Bg5 {
does not work well here because Black has a surprisingly strong way to lash
out against the Bishop:} 3... Ne4 $1 (3... e6 {would be much more cooperative,
after which White could count on a pleasant position with} 4. e3 Be7 5. Bd3 c5
6. c3 O-O 7. Nbd2 {etc.})) 3... e6 {Black continues to copy White's setup.} (
3... Bf5 {
White should treat this move just like 2...Bf5 -- either with c4 or with Bd3.}
4. c4 (4. Bd3 Bxd3 (4... e6 5. Bxf5 exf5 6. Qd3 $14) 5. cxd3 $14) 4... c6 5.
Nc3 {With this move, White sets up a formation that the current World Champion,
Magnus Carlsen, has used multiple times with devastating effect.} {
Carlsen's idea is very simple: after} 5... e6 {he plays} 6. Nh4 {
to win the Bishop pair.} 6... Bg6 (6... Bg4 $6 {
is worse, since White gets the Bishop pair anyway after} 7. Qb3 Qc7 (7... Qb6)
8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bg2 $1 {(defending the Rook on h1 so
that Black cannot exploit the pin on the h-file with ...Nxg4) and White has
some nice extra space on the kingside.}) (6... Bd6 {
is an even worse way to lose the Bishop pair, since White continues with} 7.
Nxf5 exf5 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Bd3 $14 {when Black's pawns are rather weak.}) 7.
Nxg6 hxg6 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. h3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 {White has a little
extra space -- not much -- and the pair of Bishops. In Carlsen's hands, that
is enough of an advantage that he has consistently been able to outplay the
world's best players from this sort of position.}) (3... Bg4 {It looks very
natural for Black to pin the Knight. But in this precise position, where White
has not yet played Bd3, there is a tactical problem with the pin.} 4. h3 $1 Bh5
({Giving up the Bishop pair with} 4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3 {
is not what Black had in mind.}) 5. g4 $1 Bg6 6. Ne5 $1 {White does not
normally go chasing a piece in this fashion, but here there is a very specific
idea that makes it a good plan.} 6... Nbd7 7. h4 $1 {Here it is! It turns out
that Black's Bishop does not have enough retreat squares. The only way to save
the piece is to open up the h7 square, but that idea allows White to shatter
Black's pawn structure.} 7... h5 (7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nd7 9. h5 Be4 10. f3 Bxf3
11. Qxf3 Nxe5 12. Qf4) (7... h6 8. Nxg6 fxg6 {
and now White has a very pleasant choice of ways to torment Black.} 9. Bd3 (9.
f4) (9. Qd3)) 8. Nxg6 fxg6 9. Bd3 $1 Kf7 10. g5 $1 Ng8 11. Qf3+ Ke8 12. Bxg6#)
4. Bd3 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 {is a normal Colle. White might have preferred a
Stonewall against this deployment, but the Colle is quite good here as well.})
2. e3 e6 {This move, played so early, is a little bit cooperative on Black's
part. However, it does let us see what is happening in this sort of position.}
(2... Nf6 {By putting a Knight here first rather than blocking in his
lightsquare Bishop with ...e6, Black preserves more options.} 3. Bd3 c5 4. c3 (
4. b3) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 (5. f4 Bg4 6. Nf3) 5... Bg4 6. Nbd2) (2... Bf5 {
This move gives White two different possible ways to continue.} 3. c4 {
This move gives the game a bit of a Queens Gambit feel. The idea is that
Black's Bishop will be missed on the queenside, a fact that White will take
advantage of by playing a quick Qb3 attacking b7.} (3. Bd3 Bxd3 4. cxd3 {
Now White will continue with Nf3, 0-0, possibly Nc3 or Nbd2, and e4.}) 3... c6
4. Nc3 (4. Qb3) 4... e6 5. Nf3 {Simple chess.} ({
GM Zdenko Kozul has made a specialty out of the odd-looking move} 5. g4 $5 Bg6
6. h4 h5 7. g5) 5... Nf6 6. Nh4 {transposes into Carlsen's system, seen above.}
) 3. Bd3 {The Colle System and the Stonewall Attack have several features in
common, and this is one of them. The N/b1 will go to d2 and the other Knight
will go to f3 -- the question is whether White will play f4 first. In this
position, where Black has voluntarily locked in his own lightsquare Bishop
with ...e6, a Stonewall Attack formation is particularly strong.} 3... Nf6 (
3... f5 $5 {is an interesting try for a Dutch Stonewall -- actually not a bad
idea in this position. Black is a tempo down vis a vis the situation with
colors reversed in the Stonewall Attack, but a single tempo doesn't matter
quite so much in a stable pattern like this. There is room for exploration
here.}) 4. Nd2 c5 5. c3 Nc6 {This is a perfect example of the sort of position
where White should play a Stonewall. Black has played ...d5 (so he cannot
control the e5 square with ...d6), but he has also played ...e6. That means
that it would create darksquare weaknesses for him also to play ...g6, and he
cannot get his B/c8 out to oppose White's Bishop (with ...f5) or to pin
White's Knight (with ...Bg4).} 6. f4 *

